\f3\b\fs32 Minimize time loss
\f2\b0 . For both of you. Often, the best thing you can do is ease off the throttle early before a brake zone, let the faster car pass, then tuck in behind it. In doing so, you may lose a few tenths of a second, but that\'92s better than arriving side-by-side with the other car and having your line (and the passing car\'92s line) messed up so you (and the other car) both lose a second or more. 
\f1\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f2\fs29\fsmilli14667 \cf5 How to Win at Sim Racing 
\f1\fs24 \cf3 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f3\b\fs32 \cf3 Be smart - think strategically
\f2\b0 . You may be able to turn faster lap times, and gain overall, by letting another car pass you and following it. It\'92s easy to get caught up in the battle, only to lose the war. Think long term. 
\f1\fs24 \

\f3\b\fs32 No more than one move to defend a pass
\f2\b0 . If the only way to avoid being passed is to block the other car, you don\'92t deserve to be in front (yet). Blocking is typically defined as making more than one move in defense. In other words, you can move to one side of the track to \'93discourage\'94 a following driver from attempting a pass, but if you make a second move back across to the other side to react to the other car, that\'92s blocking. Don\'92t do it. 
\f1\fs24 \

\f3\b\fs32 Learn from being passed
\f2\b0 . Sometimes the best thing you can do is let a faster car pass you, and then learn by following that driver. The more you learn, the faster you\'92ll drive, and the easiest way of not being passed is to drive faster. Focus on learning. 
\f1\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f2\fs32 \cf3 *** 
\f1\fs24 \

\f2\fs32 That is not all you\'92ll ever need to know to be good at racecraft, but it\'92s doubtful you\'92ll go wrong by following these guidelines; you may develop more of your own through experience. 
\f1\fs24 \

\f2\fs32 Finally, here\'92s something you should never forget: Every single car on the track with you (even simulated ones!) is driven by a fellow human being. A real person. Someone with a name, and probably friends and family. It\'92s easy to lose sight of that when you put your \'93sim helmet\'94 on and get on track. You know the way some drivers act irrationally in traffic (road rage), and say and do things that they never would if they weren\'92t inside the protective bubble of their vehicle? Often, that\'92s because the driver 
\f1\fs24 \

\f2\fs32 forgot that there was another person, just like them, in the other cars around them. Never forget you\'92re racing with another human. 
\f1\fs24 \

\f2\fs32 Also understand that humans make mistakes, and sometimes do things unintentionally. Give your fellow drivers the benefit of the doubt. 
\f1\fs24 \

\f2\fs32 Personally, there\'92s nothing better than being ahead of everyone else by thinking ahead, thinking strategically, positioning my car in the right place at the right time, and using my strengths and other drivers\'92 weaknesses to my advantage. Sure, I\'92m competitive, but not to the point of winning at all costs. If I have to resort to \'93playing dirty\'94 to win, I\'92d rather not win. It\'92s not very satisfying. Some may not agree with that outlook, but the most satisfying thing to me is knowing that I won fairly. I use all of the above guidelines to help me do that. 
